  "text": "As an additional test that SCMs predict true chromatin accessibility and not DNase I bias, we analyzed data from ATAC-seq, a technique that uses transposition to map sites of chromatin accessibility [CITATION_1] . We find that the Pearson's correlation between the raw reads derived from the two methods is 0.584 (Supplemental Fig. 6 ), indicating only a partial overlap in the chromatin accessibility signal calculated by these methods. A SCM trained on ATAC-seq data and tested on held-out ATAC-seq data achieves a genome-wide Pearson's correlation of 0.610 (Supplemental Fig. 7 ) and achieves decent predictive accuracy of thresholded peaks (AUC 0.953; PPV 0.384; TPR 0.385), revealing that a SCM is able to predict ATAC-seq data, although less accurately than it predicts DNase-seq data. We speculate that this decreased accuracy could be the result of lower ATAC-seq read counts, which could negatively impact SCM performance. We then asked whether a SCM trained on DNase-seq data could predict held-out ATACseq data. Because of the substantial differences in the raw signal, we focused on comparing the accuracy of a DNase I-trained SCM (K562) at predicting the locations of thresholded ATAC-seq peaks. The DNase I-trained SCM (K562) achieves an AUC of 0.922 in predicting thresholded ATAC-seq peaks (PPV 0.351; TPR 0.215) (Fig.  2B,C) , indicating that the SCM is able to predict sites of accessibility identified by distinct techniques.",
